[For a map of Turkey, see: http://legacy.lib.utexas.edu/maps/middle_east_and_asia/turkey_physio-2006.jpg; Ankara is central and inland. Gölbaşı is a town and district of the Ankara Province in the Central Anatolia region of Turkey, 20 km (12 mi) south of the city of Ankara: https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/G%C3%B6lba%C5%9F%C4%B1,_Ankara; "The district includes the Mogan and Eymir lakes. Although the lakes are polluted and infested with mosquitoes, the picnic areas and lakeside restaurants of Gölbaşı serve as a popular retreat from the city for the people of Ankara. A number of government departments have accommodations here, and the town is slowly but surely joining up with the city as the green space between the both disappears. Türk Telekom has their satellite ground control in the area." And thus a ready market for beef while celebrating Eid al-Adha.

Anthrax is common in Turkey and most years see outbreaks in Ankara Province in both cattle and sheep. These cattle would possibly have come by sea from Brazil, not a short voyage, and therefore stressed on arrival and distribution to the various farms. How they acquired this infection and how many out of the 50 is not stated, nor whether they were at pasture or in large corrals. Not cheap animals so any deaths would have been immediately noted and checked. Anthrax is uncommon in Brazil so they didn't bring the infection with them. - Mod.MHJ

HealthMap/ProMED map available at:
Ankara, Ankara Province, Turkey: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=5992873,706]
